<h2 id=3D"calculating-steps-miles">Calculating steps and miles</h2>
<span class=3D"fastFacts">
<p>
A person of average height and weight has a step length of between 2.1 and =
2.5 feet, meaning they=20
take <a href=3D"https://www.thecalculatorsite.com/health/how-many-steps-in-=
a-mile">around 2,250 steps to walk one mile</a> at a moderate pace of about=
 3 mph (4.8 kph).
</p>
</span>
<p>
Using this steps-per-mile walking average, we can approximate the following=
:
</p>

<ul class=3D"stepList">
	<li>A half-mile =3D 1,125 walking steps.</li>
	<li>A quarter-mile =3D 560 walking steps.</li>
	<li>5,000 steps =3D around 2 =C2=BC miles.</li>
	<li><a href=3D"https://www.thecalculatorsite.com/articles/health/10000-ste=
ps-in-miles.php">10,000 steps</a> =3D around 4 =C2=BD miles.</li>
	<li>15,000 steps =3D around 6 =C2=BE miles.</li>
	<li>20,000 steps =3D around 9 miles.</li>
</ul>

<p>
These figures are, of course, based on an average of height ranges and spee=
ds. For a more accurate conversion of steps to miles, you need to look at a=
=20
number of factors that affect your step length and the distance you cover. =
The step length of a 7ft tall runner is going to be greater than that of a =
4 ft tall walker.=20
For our steps to miles conversion to work, we therefore need to take into a=
ccount for variables such as gender, height, weight and the pace of=20
your walk or run.
</p>

<p id=3D"ref1return">
Our steps to miles calculator and the data tables below use data from a 200=
8 research study of one-mile step counts at walking and running speeds, pub=
lished=20
in the <a href=3D"https://www.acsm.org/" target=3D"_blank">American College=
 of Sports Medicine's</a> <i>Health &amp; Fitness Journal</i>. In the study=
, researchers set out to find out the number of steps individuals took at v=
arious speeds of walking and=20
running. They then examined the differences for men and women and extrapola=
ted the data out for individual heights. It's important to note that all pe=
ople=20
studied were regarded as being of 'normal weight'. <a class=3D"referenceTag=
" href=3D"https://www.thecalculatorsite.com/health/steps-miles.php#ref1" re=
l=3D"nofollow" title=3D"Go to reference 1">1</a>
</p>
<p>
To get the most accurate calculation, it's best to measure your personal st=
ep length and use that data. We discuss how to do this later on in our arti=
cle.
</p>

