<a href=3D"https://www.thecalculatorsite.com/health/steps-miles.php#faq" re=
l=3D"nofollow" class=3D"returnToList"><svg><use xlink:href=3D"#arrowTurnUp"=
></use></svg></a>
<h2 id=3D"how-to-calculate">How to calculate steps to miles</h2>
<p>
If you want to manually calculate how many steps you take when walking or r=
unning for your personal measurements, you can use this formula:
</p>

<div class=3D"fullquote" style=3D"padding-bottom:20px;">
miles =3D steps =C3=97 step length (inches) / 63,360
</div>

<p>
If you want the formula in feet, it looks like this:
</p>

<div class=3D"fullquote" style=3D"padding-bottom:20px;">
miles =3D steps =C3=97 step length (feet) / 5,280
</div>

<p id=3D"ref7return">
Let's go through the calculation steps, which will require a conversion. Fo=
r step 1, you will need a tape measure or other measuring device. If you wa=
nt to skip this part, you=20
can get a rough calculation by using average step lengths: 26 inches for a =
woman and 30 inches for a man. <a class=3D"referenceTag" href=3D"https://ww=
w.thecalculatorsite.com/health/steps-miles.php#ref7" rel=3D"nofollow" title=
=3D"Go to reference 7">7</a>
</p>

<ol class=3D"cList">
 <li><strong>Measure your step length</strong>. Take 10 steps (making sure =
you either run or walk, depending on which step length you want to measure)=
. Measure the=20
 distance in inches and then divide by 10 to get your average step length.<=
/li>
 <li><strong>Multiply your step length</strong> by the number of steps you'=
ve taken. E.g. 26 inches =C3=97 5,000 =3D 130,000 inches.</li>
 <li><strong>Convert your inch figure to miles</strong> by dividing it by 6=
3,360 (<a href=3D"https://www.thecalculatorsite.com/conversions/lengthanddi=
stance.php">converter here</a>). 130,000 inches / 63,360 =3D 2.1 miles.</li=
>
</ol>

<p>
It's worth remembering that step length and stride length are different, as=
 the University of Oklahoma Health Sciences Center's stride analysis=20
explains <a class=3D"referenceTag" href=3D"https://www.thecalculatorsite.co=
m/health/steps-miles.php#ref7" rel=3D"nofollow" title=3D"Go to reference 7"=
>7</a>
</p>

<div class=3D"fullquote" style=3D"font-size:18px; line-height:22px;">
<ul>
 <li style=3D"margin-bottom:20px;"><strong>Step length</strong> is the dist=
ance between the heel contact of one foot and the heel contact of the oppos=
ite foot.</li>
 <li><strong>Stride length</strong> is the distance between the heel contac=
t of two successive placements of the same foot.</li>
</ul>
</div>

<p>
The definition of a step also varies depending on the measurement tool. As =
an example, both Fitbit and Apple Watch have their own proprietary algorith=
ms that=20
determine what constitutes a step, based on acceleration. In research, it's=
 common to use more accurate devices such as actigraphs. It's therefore wor=
th=20
bearing in mind that steps will vary depending on what you are using to mea=
sure them.
</p>


<!-- Ezoic - Longer Content 151 - longer_content -->
<div id=3D"ezoic-pub-ad-placeholder-151"></div>
<!-- End Ezoic - Longer Content 151 - longer_content -->


<a href=3D"https://www.thecalculatorsite.com/health/steps-miles.php#faq" re=
l=3D"nofollow" class=3D"returnToList"><svg><use xlink:href=3D"#arrowTurnUp"=
></use></svg></a>
<h2 id=3D"age-stride-length">Does age affect step/stride length?</h2>
<p id=3D"ref3return">
There are a couple of studies of particular note relating to <a href=3D"htt=
ps://www.thecalculatorsite.com/misc/age-calculator.php">age</a> and step/st=
ride length. In a 2000 study in=20
the <i>Journal of Applied Physiology</i>, Professor Paul DeVita and his col=
league Tibor Hortobagyi set out to examine the joint torques and powers of=
=20
young and elderly adults walking at the same speed. They discovered that th=
e older people get, the less they use the muscles in their ankles to make e=
ach stride,=20
and the more they use the muscles around their hips. Stride length was foun=
d to be 4% shorter in elderly adult walkers compared with young adults.=20
<a class=3D"referenceTag" href=3D"https://www.thecalculatorsite.com/health/=
steps-miles.php#ref3" rel=3D"nofollow" title=3D"Go to reference 3">3</a>
</p>
<p id=3D"ref4return">
In a follow-up study published in <i>Medicine &amp; Science in Sports &amp;=
 Exercise</i> in 2016, Dr. DeVita and his team looked to examine the biomec=
hanics of a set of healthy, recreational runners between the=20
ages of 23 and 59. As participants ran at their regular training pace, moti=
on and force data were captured, and the data were then analyzed and correl=
ated with age.=20
<a class=3D"referenceTag" href=3D"https://www.thecalculatorsite.com/health/=
steps-miles.php#ref4" rel=3D"nofollow" title=3D"Go to reference 4">4</a>
</p>
<p>
Their research findings suggest that with each passing year, a runner's str=
ide length and speed decrease by an average of 0.33%. By the time a 20-year=
-old runner reaches the age of 80, their stride length may have decreased=
=20
by as much as 20%.
</p>

<a href=3D"https://www.thecalculatorsite.com/health/steps-miles.php#faq" re=
l=3D"nofollow" class=3D"returnToList"><svg><use xlink:href=3D"#arrowTurnUp"=
></use></svg></a>
<h2 id=3D"step-targets">How many steps is enough?</h2>
<p>
You'll likely have heard the adage of taking 10,000 steps a day to help mai=
ntain a healthy lifestyle. You may not know that this message
<a href=3D"https://www.zmescience.com/science/how-steps-a-day-should-i-walk=
/" target=3D"_blank">originated from a series of Japanese marketing campaig=
ns</a> run=20
around the time of the 1964 Tokyo Olympics. Spotting an increased focus on =
fitness and exercise in the general population, Dr Yoshiro Hatano introduce=
d a pedometer=20
called the Manpo-kei (which translates to <i>10,000 step meter</i>) in 1965=
. The 10,000 steps concept took off and gradually spread worldwide as an ac=
hievable=20
daily target for maintaining good health. However, there has never been any=
 great science behind it.
</p>

<div class=3D"photobox_main photoborder" style=3D"padding:0;">
<img src=3D"https://www.thecalculatorsite.com/images/health/manpo-kei-meter=
.jpg" alt=3D"Manpo-kei (10,000 steps meter)">
<span style=3D"display:block; padding:5px 10px 10px 10px; font-size:13px; l=
ine-height:13px;">The Manpo-kei (10,000 steps meter) from 1965. <span style=
=3D"color:#aaa;">Credit: Yoshida1338</span></span>
</div>
<p id=3D"ref8return">
Until recently, step numbers have not been the focus of many studies into e=
xercise and health. Research instead focussed on time in different activity=
 intensities, such as light, moderate and vigorous. However, the rise of te=
chnology has=20
meant that steps are being seen as a more intuitive measurement for people.=
 And so we're beginning to see studies looking at step counts. In November =
2021, a study published in the <i>Journal of Internal Medicine</i> found th=
at=20
a figure of 7,500 steps is associated with lower risk of early death. <a cl=
ass=3D"referenceTag" href=3D"https://www.thecalculatorsite.com/health/steps=
-miles.php#ref8" rel=3D"nofollow" title=3D"Go to reference 8">8</a>
</p>
<p id=3D"ref9return">
In addition to this, another 2021 study of 2,110 adults, with an average fo=
llow-up of 10.8 years, found that participants who took at least 7,000 step=
s per day had a=20
50% to 70% lower risk of mortality compared with those taking fewer than 7,=
000 steps per day. The study, published in <i>JAMA</i>,=20
suggests that "higher daily step volume was associated with a lower risk of=
 premature all-cause mortality among Black and White middle-aged women and =
men."=20
<a class=3D"referenceTag" href=3D"https://www.thecalculatorsite.com/health/=
steps-miles.php#ref9" rel=3D"nofollow" title=3D"Go to reference 9">9</a>
</p>
<p>
In November 2021, the <a href=3D"https://scholars.duke.edu/display/pub14976=
39" target=3D"_blank">Steps for Health Collaborative</a> conducted a meta-a=
nalysis of seven studies with device-measured steps-per-day. They followed =
participants for cardiovascular disease events (disorders of the heart and =
blood vessels) over time. Importantly, these studies=20
didn't rely on self-reporting data, instead using step counters to ensure a=
ccuracy. The researchers found that the risk of cardiovascular disease fell=
 as the number of steps increased. Indeed, the most active group had less t=
han half the number of cardiovascular disease events=20
than the least active (243 versus 491).
</p>
<p>
Amanda Paluch, a lead researcher and assistant professor in the School of P=
ublic Health and Health Sciences at the University of Massachusetts in Amhe=
rst, said:
</p>
<p id=3D"ref10return">
</p><blockquote>"The message is to move more. Don't get caught up in 10,000=
 or any other number. It is not an all or nothing situation for cardiovascu=
lar health benefits. Just getting incremental increases in your steps could=
 be=20
meaningful in your cardiovascular health." <a class=3D"referenceTag" href=
=3D"https://www.thecalculatorsite.com/health/steps-miles.php#ref10" rel=3D"=
nofollow" title=3D"Go to reference 10">10</a></blockquote>
<p></p>
<p>
Dr. Felipe Lobelo, who heads Emory University's <i>Exercise is Medicine (EI=
M)</i> Global Research and Collaboration Center, and was not involved in th=
e research, reinforced the message that came from it:
</p>
<p>
</p><blockquote>"This research shows that the number of steps we should be =
striving for to generate benefits for cardiovascular disease is lower than =
10,000, maybe between 5,000 and 6,000 steps per day, which is pretty much t=
he equivalent of 150=20
minutes per week," <a class=3D"referenceTag" href=3D"https://www.thecalcula=
torsite.com/health/steps-miles.php#ref10" rel=3D"nofollow" title=3D"Go to r=
eference 10">10</a></blockquote>
<p></p>
<p id=3D"ref5return">
The NHS in England has also adopted the 150-minute-per-week message. For ma=
ny years it promoted a '10,000 steps challenge', suggesting that "setting y=
ourself a target of=20
walking 10,000 steps a day can be a fun way of increasing the amount of phy=
sical activity you do." This guidance has now changed to highlight short, b=
risk walks and a=20
recommended 150 minutes of weekly exercise. <a class=3D"referenceTag" href=
=3D"https://www.thecalculatorsite.com/health/steps-miles.php#ref5" rel=3D"n=
ofollow" title=3D"Go to reference 5">5</a>
</p>
<p>
And the intensity of the walk is the key thing here. A person will expend m=
ore energy (burn more calories) walking briskly than taking a gentle stroll=
.=20
</p>

<div class=3D"fullquote" id=3D"ref6return">
<p>
"Research shows that a total amount of at least 150 minutes a week of moder=
ate-intensity aerobic activity, such as brisk walking, consistently reduces=
 the risk of many=20
chronic diseases and other adverse health outcomes"=20
<a class=3D"referenceTag" href=3D"https://www.thecalculatorsite.com/health/=
steps-miles.php#ref6" rel=3D"nofollow" title=3D"Go to reference 6">6</a>
</p>
<p style=3D"font-size:13px;">
<i>Physical Activity Guidelines for Americans</i>
</p>
</div>

<p id=3D"ref11return">
The time of day that you exercise may also be important to maximise the bes=
t result. A study published in <i>Frontiers in Physiology</i> found women b=
urned more body fat during morning exercise, whereas=20
evening exercise was "ideal for men interested in improving heart and metab=
olic health, as well as emotional wellbeing." <a class=3D"referenceTag" hre=
f=3D"https://www.thecalculatorsite.com/health/steps-miles.php#ref11" rel=3D=
"nofollow" title=3D"Go to reference 11">11</a>
</p>


<!-- Ezoic - Longest Content - longest_content -->
<div id=3D"ezoic-pub-ad-placeholder-164"></div>
<!-- End Ezoic - Longest Content - longest_content -->


<a href=3D"https://www.thecalculatorsite.com/health/steps-miles.php#faq" re=
l=3D"nofollow" class=3D"returnToList"><svg><use xlink:href=3D"#arrowTurnUp"=
></use></svg></a>
<h2 id=3D"calories">Calculating calories burned</h2>
<p>
Let's shift focus a little to calorie burn. You may be wondering how many c=
alories you're burning with your daily step count. We use METS (metabolic e=
quivalents) data=20
from the <a href=3D"https://sites.google.com/site/compendiumofphysicalactiv=
ities/" target=3D"_blank">Compendium of Physical Activities</a> to calculat=
e the number=20
of <a href=3D"https://www.thecalculatorsite.com/health/steps-to-calories.ph=
p">calories you've burned</a> on your walk or run. Your body is said to bur=
n 3.5ml of oxygen per kilogram of bodyweight per minute=20
when sitting still. Sitting still is given a MET value of 1. MET values the=
n increase based upon the activity.
</p>

<div class=3D"fullquote">
<h3 style=3D"margin-top:0px;">Formula for calories burned per minute</h3>
<p>
(MET =C3=97 weight in kg =C3=97 3.5) =C3=B7 200
</p>
</div>

<p>
Remember that calculations will vary depending on several factors, includin=
g your metabolism. You can=20
<a href=3D"https://www.thecalculatorsite.com/health/bmr-calculator.php">cal=
culate your Basal Metabolic Rate (BMR) here</a> and find out your daily cal=
orie requirement if you need to.
</p>

<h3>Calories burned per mile when walking</h3>
<p>
An average adult man (suggested to be about 200 pounds, or 91kg) burns roug=
hly 106 calories walking one mile. For an=20
average adult woman (suggested to be about 170 pounds, or 77kg), the figure=
 will be about 90 calories per mile.
</p>
<p>
To estimate how many calories you burn for each mile of walking, multiply y=
our weight in pounds by 0.53 (or kg weight =C3=97 1.17).
</p>
<p>
Note that these figures assume that you're not carrying extra weight. Walki=
ng while weighted is said to burn more calories than walking without weight=
s because you're expending more energy to carry that extra weight. There's =
also a level of fitness to consider -=20
the fitter you are, the more fuel-efficient you become. Your average calori=
c expenditure per one mile of walking is therefore likely to vary.
</p>

<h3>Calories burned per mile when running</h3>
<p>
An average adult male (suggested to be about 200 pounds, or 91kg) burns rou=
ghly 150 calories per mile when running (unweighted). An average adult fema=
le=20
(suggested to be about 170 pounds, or 77kg) might expect to burn around 128=
 calories.
</p>
<p>
To calculate the number of calories you burn when running a mile, multiply =
your weight in pounds by 0.75 (or kg weight =C3=97 1.65).
</p>

<p>
